The following formula was used to determine the amount of solvent to be added for making the extract solution for antibacterial activity test.
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{Amount}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{solvent}\ \mathrm{to}\ \mathrm{be}\ \mathrm{added}=\frac{100\times \mathrm{amount}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{extract}\ \mathrm{obtained}}{\mathrm{amount}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{plant}\ \mathrm{powder}\ \mathrm{used}} $$\end{document}Amount of solvent tobeadded=100×amount of extract obtainedamount of plant powder used

The following formula was used for calculating the activity index:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{Activity}\ \mathrm{index}=\frac{\mathrm{zone}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{inhibition}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{plant}\ \mathrm{extract}}{\mathrm{zone}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{inhibition}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathrm{antibiotic}\ \mathrm{disc}} $$\end{document}Activity index=zone of inhibition of plant extractzone of inhibition of antibiotic disc
